 cheap buttered biscuit sat on his lap, half-eaten. Biscuits went on the plate. *That\u2019s how you know he\u2019s lying.* \n\n\u201c*Lupa*,\u201d he said, leaning in. His breath smelled of wet wool and desperation. Not like before. Not like gin and biscuits. Like fear-sweat. \u201cWe need\u2026 a distraction. Something personal. Something *real*.\u201d His hand brushed her thigh. Not a caress. A test. *Is she here yet?* \n\nHer bones went cold. Cold like the time Voldemort asked herself why the prophecy felt like a splinter. She didn\u2019t flinch. Her eyes stayed locked on the Snorkack\u2014eyes wide, grey like dusk. *See? He\u2019s talking nonsense. He doesn\u2019t see you. He never* does. \n\nHe didn\u2019t wait. His flies opened. Not poetic. Not graceful. Just *open*. A dry crack, like twigs snapping. His dick slapped against his knee. Thick. Veined. Angry red. *Adult. Not boy, not child. Like one of Hagrid\u2019s hedgehogs after too much cider.* \n\nNo words. No \u201cLuna dearest.\u201d His hands shoved her head down. Not hard. Not soft. *Useless.* Her lips met skin\u2014sour, salt-sting, the faintest tip of him *inside*. She didn\u2019t gag. Didn\u2019t breathe. Her mouth went numb. Like sucking on a cold toad. She stared at the Snorkack\u2019s tail feathers. *Thirteen. Lopsided. Stupid.* \n\nHis grunt was loud. Brutal. *Fuck. Shame. Mine.* She felt the heat on her chin, the sticky thread she wiped fast with her sleeve. Didn\u2019t look up. Didn\u2019t blink. Felt the cold tile under her knees. Smelled the ink on his skin. Tasted the panic\u2014*deep*, sour\u2014mixed with the salt. \n\nWhen it was over, he zipped up. Fixed his glasses. Patted her shoulder. \u201cSee? That\u2019s the proof. They\u2019ll believe me now.\u201d \n\nShe stood. Adjusted her skirt. Rubbed her jaw. *Left ear\u2019s ringing.* Outside, the Snorkack twitched and died. She picked up her rabbit file. Walked to the sink. Opened the tap. Turned it on full. Watched the water swirl down. *